[3] Pakistan - parental differences on vaccination - media report
Date: Fri 5 Jul 2019
Source: Vaccine confidence Project, a The Times UK report [edited]
https://www.vaccineconfidence.org/pakistan-husband-divorces-wife-for-vaccinating-their-family-against-polio/


A woman who was divorced by her husband for having their children inoculated against polio has condemned the "anti-vax" campaign that is sweeping Pakistan. [The 26 year old woman], was at home with her children when a vaccination team arrived in the area, on the outskirts of Karachi 2 weeks ago. Her husband was at work but had left strict instructions that the children were not to receive the vaccine. "He had often fought with me about vaccinations. He said they were suspicious and damaged children's health," [she] said.

Rumours have spread like wildfire across Pakistan in recent weeks, fuelled by a series of lurid videos posted on social media claiming that scores of children who had taken polio drops during a recent vaccination drive had fallen ill soon afterwards and died. Health clinics were set on fire and thousands of families have refused to let their children be vaccinated as a result, frustrating a government push to declare Pakistan polio free.

[This woman] had not been swayed by the panic and, unknown to her husband, she had already had their 4-year-old son, and their 9-month-old daughter vaccinated at her parents' house against other diseases. When the polio team knocked at her door, she immediately ushered them inside.

"My main concern is the health of my children. My daughter is getting weaker and I could not skip the polio vaccination drops out of fear of my husband," she said. This time, though, she could not conceal her deception: the polio team marked the children's fingers with indelible ink. When [her husband] came home and realised what had happened he flew into a rage and divorced her on the spot, the husband said, using the "triple talaq" practice that grants a Muslim man instant divorce by saying the word "talaq" -- divorce in Arabic -- 3 times. [She] and her children were thrown out of the house.

Pakistan is 1 of only 3 countries where polio has not been wiped out, along with Afghanistan and Nigeria. Despite a vaccination drive that has reached almost 40 million children this year [2019], there have been at least 37 confirmed polio cases, almost triple the number recorded last year [2018].

Facebook, Twitter and YouTube have pulled down at least 200 videos falsely claiming that hundreds of children died after vaccinations. However, Islamist militants are still attacking vaccination teams, believing them to be a conspiracy to sterilise Muslim children or a cover for western spy agencies. The Pakistani vaccination drive was halted for several days after a health worker and 2 police officers guarding her were shot and killed in May [2019].

Now living at her mother's house, [the woman] said that [her husband] was "pleading to come back, but our relationship is over, according to Islam. I support the vaccination campaign against this crippling disease. It is vital for the children. I will not take any risks with my children's health."

[Byline: Haroon Janjua & Hugh Tomlinson]

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[The above article is an example of what is driving the anti-vaccination movement in terms of the impact of social media and the personal toll it is taking in households in Pakistan (and one suspects elsewhere around the world where the antivaccination movement has taken hold). A very sad state of affairs. And while the impact of this movement has been demonstrated clearly this year with the rise of measles cases globally, one shouldn't ignore the impact it is having on polio transmission around the world, with an almost doubling of the number of cases of WPV1 during 2019 to date, and the increasing number of countries demonstrating cVDPV during the past 12 months. - Mod.MPP]
